Programming Language Mascots
===============================================================================

%% Programming language mascots have become an integral part of the programming community, serving as symbols of identity, culture, and fun for various languages. From the historic Logo Turtle to Ferris the crab for Rust, these mascots not only represent their respective languages but also foster a sense of community among developers. In this article, we will explore the history, significance, and impact of programming language mascots, highlighting some of the most iconic ones and their contributions to the programming world. We'll cover their origins, design inspirations, and the role they play in marketing and community building.

***

I've looked around, I can't find any good articles on the history of programming language mascots. So I thought I'd write one!

This article tries to cover the past present and future of programming language mascots, exploring their origins, significance, and impact on the programming community.

We'll look at the most iconic mascots, their design inspirations, and how they contribute to the identity and culture of programming languages. We'll also look at some newer mascots and trends in mascot design, as well as the role of mascots in marketing and community building.

This kind of topic collects knowledge that may only be contained in scattered blog posts, forum discussions, and social media threads, so I hope this article serves as a comprehensive resource for anyone interested in the fascinating world of programming language mascots. If I've gotten any of the history wrong, let me know, I'd like this post to be accurate and authoritative for this topic.


1. History of mascots in computing
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Computing used to be a largely academic, business, and military endeavor and therefore serious in nature. But that of course never stopped people and subcultures within computing from having fun and expressing themselves creatively, and sometime even in silly ways. As the field grew and diversified -- and also commercialized -- the need for branding and user engagement led to the widespread adoption of mascots. Moreover, programming languages began to form communities of users around them, and mascots served as a way to foster a sense of identity to help the community bond and express their shared identity under the language's banner.

REDDit USER ASKS WHY DO PROGRAMMING LANGUAGES HAVE MASCOTS?

Good question! 

- Branding and Marketing: Mascots help create a memorable image for a programming language, making it easier for developers to recognize and remember it among many options.
- Community Building: Mascots can foster a sense of community and belonging among users of a programming language, helping to create a shared identity.
- Engagement and Fun: Mascots add an element of fun and personality to a programming language, making it more approachable and engaging for users.
- Differentiation: In a crowded market of programming languages, mascots help differentiate one language from another, making it stand out.
- Cultural Significance: Mascots can embody the values, philosophy, or characteristics of a programming language, reflecting its design principles or intended use cases.

But when it comes down to it, they're just fun. Programming languages are abstract concepts, and mascots give them a tangible, relatable form that can make them more representable in forms like logos, merchandise, and documentation.

So let's take a look at the history of programming language mascots and some of the most iconic ones out there!

The idea of applying mascot branding to computing products dates back to 1976 when BSD Unix adopted the BSD Daemon, also known as Beastie, as its mascot [BEASTIE]. The character was created by artist Marshall Kirk McKusick and has since become one of the most recognizable symbols in the Unix community.

Designed by:

Phil Foglio
Mike O'Brien
John Lasseter



In this case the mascot is a daemon as an allusion to the idea of a background process in Unix systems, which are often referred to as "daemons." This started the tradition of using the mascot to represent and personify features of the operating system, although as we'll see the origin stories and meanings behind them can have varying levels of depth. 

Since the introduction of the BSD Daemon, the open source community has frequently used mascots to represent various projects and movements including the GNU Project's GNU (a wildebeest), Linux's Tux the penguin, Glenda the Plan 9 bunny, the Android robot, and many others.

(?)> Why doesn't Windows have a mascot, you might be wondering? Well, there *are* several unofficial Windows mascots created by fans called OS-tans, anime anthropomorphizations of the various Windows operating systems that have been popular in fringe internet culture. It started when users of Windows ME started drawing anthropomorphized characters to represent the operating system, often portraying it as a girl with a somewhat unstable personality, which is supposed to reflect the reputation Windows ME had for being buggy and unreliable. I had started looking into this but it gets very weird very fast, so I'll leave it as an exercise for the reader to delve into that rabbit hole.

2. Early programming language mascots
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(1.1) The Original PL Mascot -- The Logo Turtle

So when did programming languages start getting mascots of their own?

The first programming language mascot is arguably the Logo Turtle, which was introduced in the late 1960s as part of the Logo programming language. 

https://youtu.be/cwnMhI9XjO8?si=FV8zG9Tj6PHoqrjg&t=614

Originally, the turtle was a physical robot that could be programmed to move around and draw shapes, but it later evolved into a graphical representation on computer screens called Turtle Graphics, which is what most people think of when they recall Logo [TURTLE]. The idea behind Logo was that it was designed to be more accessible to children by taking advantage of their natural ability to understand spatial relationships and movement. Whereas most languages of the time (and still today really) expected a level of abstract reasoning that was beyond the level of children, logo sought to meet them at their level by providing a visual and interactive way to learn programming concepts.



The turtle was essentially the programmer's avatar in the programming environment, giving them a tangible way to see the results of their code, and allowed them to debug by putting themselves in the turtle's shoes and reasoning from its perspective. This design allowed Logo to be used by children as young as four years old, making it one of the earliest examples of a programming language designed specifically for educational purposes.

The turtle got its name from the physical turtle robots used in the early implementations of the Logo language, some of which featured a dome-like enclosure that resembled a turtle's shell. The turtle mascot has since become an iconic symbol of the Logo programming language and is often used in educational materials and programming environments that support Logo. Even the Turtle robot has lived on in the Open Robotics Initiative, which has released a TurtleBot series of robots for education and research.


(2.2) Perl

- "Programming perl" came out with the camel on the cover
- It became associated with Perl
- The camel is an unofficial mascot for Perl due to the association but O'Reilly has control over it and grants permission to the community to use it
- There is no symbolic meaning behind the camel really, it was chosen for the book cover becasue the rights were available and it matched the style O'Reilly used at the time of having engravings of animals on their book covers. It could have easily been any other animal.
- However, you'll still see the camel used in Perl-related contexts, such as conferences and merchandise, as a nod to the language's history and culture.
- Which is unfortunate because OCaml has a much clearer association to camels.
- Moreover, the Perl foundation uses an Onion as their logo. That and the control O'Reilly has over the camel means that Perl doesn't really have a true community mascot.

